ename probably arises from an Old English personal name <i>Sǣga</i> or a stream-name <i>Sǣge</i> (from Old English <i>sǣge</i> ‘slow moving’; compare   Seabrook  ) + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","Scottish: habitational name from Seton (East Lothian), from Old English <i>sǣ</i> ‘sea’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Seton","meanings":["Scottish (Midlothian) and English: variant of   Seaton  ."]},{"name":"Seeton","meanings":["Scottish or English: variant of   Seaton  ."]},{"name":"Sitton","meanings":["English (London): possibly a variant of   Seaton  .","Jewish (from the Ottoman Empire): variant of   Sutton  ."]},{"name":"Seabrook","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Hertfordshire): habitational name from Seabrook in Ivinghoe (Buckinghamshire), possibly from an Old English personal name <i>Sǣga</i> or Old English <i>sǣge</i> ‘slow moving’ + <i>brōc</i> ‘brook, stream’."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":65,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was com